{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653065"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:42:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:42:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18556"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18556"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11288"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75656"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11288"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18556"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61174"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"10812"},{"type":"tags","id":"10844"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26172"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26907"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75656"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA laboratory technician is processing stool samples to identify potential enteric pathogens. The samples are plated onto MacConkey agar, a commonly used selective medium.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary selective function of MacConkey agar?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits growth of gram-positive bacteria","Promotes growth of anaerobic bacteria","Selects for fungal growth","Promotes growth of acid-fast bacteria","Inhibits growth of gram-negative bacteria"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMacConkey agar \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibits growth of gram-positive bacteria\u003C/strong\u003E through the presence of bile salts and crystal violet. This selective property makes it particularly useful for isolating gram-negative enteric pathogens from stool samples.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotes growth of anaerobic bacteria\u003C/strong\u003E - MacConkey agar is used in aerobic conditions and does not specifically support anaerobic growth\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits growth of gram-negative bacteria\u003C/strong\u003E - MacConkey agar actually promotes the growth of gram-negative bacteria while inhibiting gram-positive organisms\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelects for fungal growth\u003C/strong\u003E - MacConkey agar is not designed for fungal culture; specific media like Sabouraud agar are used for fungi\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotes growth of acid-fast bacteria\u003C/strong\u003E - Specialised media like L\u00f6wenstein-Jensen medium are required for acid-fast bacteria\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EIn addition to its selective properties, MacConkey agar contains lactose and neutral red indicator which allows differentiation between lactose-fermenting and non-lactose-fermenting organisms based on colony colour.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Selective media contain specific ingredients that allow certain microorganisms to grow while inhibiting others.","MacConkey agar contains bile salts and crystal violet which inhibit gram-positive bacteria while allowing gram-negative bacteria to grow.","Indicator dyes in selective media can help differentiate between organisms based on their metabolic characteristics."],"references":["Murray PR, Rosenthal KS, Pfaller MA. Medical Microbiology. 8th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61174"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18556"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61174"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T13:13:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T13:16:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11288"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75656"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4944"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Microbiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10